<p><strong>Feral Pig (<em>Sus scrofa</em>)</strong></p>
<p><strong>Family: </strong>Suidae<br />
<strong>Genus Species: </strong><em>Sus scrofa</em><br />
<strong>Common Name: </strong>Feral Pig, Wild Pig<br /><p>
<p><strong>Identification</strong></p>
<p>The Feral Pig has a length of 3½-5 feet, a height of 3 feet, and a weight of up to 400 pounds. Its hair is coarse and thin, and its upper tusks are curved upward. It has four toes on each foot. For a more detailed overview of this species see 〔<a href="http://www.enature.com/fieldguides/detail.asp?allSpecies=y&amp;searchText=feral%20pig&amp;curGroupID=5&amp;lgfromWhere=&amp;curPageNum=1" target="_blank">eNature</a>〕.</p>
<p><strong> </strong></p>
<p><strong>Habitat Associations and Natural History</strong></p>
<p>The habitat for this pig is variable, but it can be found in densely forested mountainous terrains, brushland, dry ridges, and swamps. It is active at dusk and dawn, and can run fast and swim well. It feeds mainly on acorns, beech, hickory, pecan nuts, roots, tubers, grasses, fruits, and berries. It also preys on crayfish, frogs, snakes, salamanders, mice, eggs of birds, and carrion. It bears 4-12 young twice a year and has a gestation period of 16-17 weeks.</p>
